We seem to *mostly* agree here then.  Note that one of my examples of varying mana regen situations was no slower/no CC.  I agree with you that some situations you have so much mana that it really doesn't matter that a wizard is overnuking or whatever...  and typically in those situations if I have to heal a little more because of overaggro, I may suck it up for longer before I start getting indignant.  On the other hand, it is still shoddy playing and I may eventually say something as a matter of principle...  you don't want to set a precedent here that shoddy playing is ok.  When you *DO* need a wizard to control aggro finely, you can't wait for them to learn how to do it...  they need to have practiced and to be aware of when it is imperative to do it without being told.  Which lends itself to the next question, which is 'If controlling your aggro is a fine and good thing in tight situations, and can be the difference between the cleric having enough mana to keep the group alive or not, why not do it all the time if you can?'  If everybody in the group decides not to put in as much effort and play crappily because they have that margin, not only does the group efficiency and therefore kill rate go way down, but when you get a couple adds and suddenly have to switch from lazy mode to kickass mode, it may already be too late, or you may not make the switch fast enough...  Playing well all the time &gt; Playing well only when you have to.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I never said that I kept wizards alive with elixir only, I just said that I didn't keep SR memmed. SL, SE, CE and arb have always been enough for me to keep anyone alive. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
